.max-w-prose
  = doc_info(url: "https://github.com/profoundry-us/loco_motion/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md", icon: "arrow-up-circle", icon_css: "text-primary") do
    :markdown
      Until _Loco_**Motion** reaches 1.0.0, **every minor release should be
      considered breaking**. This guide walks through everything you need to
      change; the CHANGELOG has the full details.

.prose
  :markdown
    # Upgrading LocoMotion

    This guide covers upgrading from **v0.6.0 to v0.7.0**. It is a big
    release: the Labelable `start` / `end` API is renamed, icons render
    through the new `loco_icon` engine, and checkboxes submit like Rails
    checkboxes. Three new components (Megamenu, OTP, and Aura) come along
    for the ride.

- # The roadmap: four action sections plus the victory lap. The colored
- # steps link to their section below. The links opt out of Turbo because
- # the layout wraps pages in a turbo-frame, which would otherwise swallow
- # same-page anchor jumps.
.mt-8.rounded-box.border.border-base-300.p-6
  = daisy_steps(css: "w-full steps-vertical sm:steps-horizontal") do |steps|
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#packages", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Update packages
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#rename", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Rename labels
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#icons", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Migrate icons
    - steps.with_step(css: "step-primary") do
      %a{ href: "#checkboxes", class: "link-hover", data: { turbo: "false" } } Review forms
    - steps.with_step(title: "Enjoy 0.7.0 🎉")

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "packages", class: "scroll-mt-24" } 1. Update your packages
  :markdown
    Bump the gem and the matching npm package. The new Megamenu, OTP, and
    Aura components rely on styles introduced in **DaisyUI 5.6**, so the
    npm package now declares `daisyui` `^5.6.0` as a peer dependency —
    bump it alongside:

.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(css: "my-4", language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # Gemfile
      gem "loco_motion-rails", "~> 0.7.0"

.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(css: "my-4") do |code|
    - code.with_line(prefix: "$") do
      yarn add @profoundry-us/loco_motion@0.7.0
    - code.with_line(prefix: "$") do
      yarn add daisyui@^5.6.7

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "rename", class: "flex flex-col items-start gap-2 scroll-mt-24" }
    = daisy_badge("Breaking", css: "badge-error badge-soft")
    %span 2. Rename start / end to leading / trailing
  :markdown
    The `start` / `end` pair is renamed everywhere: `start` is now
    **`leading`** and `end` is now **`trailing`**. (`end` is a Ruby reserved
    word, so its generated slot reader forced `send(:end)` workarounds; the
    new pair is symmetric and reserved-word free.) This is a **hard rename
    with no deprecation aliases**, affecting:

    - The labelable inputs (and their form-builder equivalents like
      `f.daisy_checkbox`): `daisy_text_input` (and its `daisy_input` alias),
      `daisy_select`, `daisy_checkbox`, `daisy_toggle`, `daisy_radio`, and
      `daisy_cally_input`
    - The Navbar's `start` / `end` slots (`center` is unchanged)
    - The Timeline event's `start` / `end` slots and its
      `with_event(start:, end:)` options (`middle` / `middle_icon` are
      unchanged)
    - The Modal's `start_actions` / `end_actions` slots and parts, which
      become `leading_actions` / `trailing_actions`

    Every spelling of the pair changes — keyword arguments, slot calls, and
    the generated part options:

- # The rename map as a real table (dogfooding daisy_table) — far easier
- # to scan than the prose bullets it replaces.
.mt-4.overflow-x-auto.rounded-box.border.border-base-300
  = daisy_table(css: "table-zebra") do |table|
    - table.with_head do |head|
      - head.with_column { "Before" }
      - head.with_column { "After" }
      - head.with_column { "Applies to" }
    - renames.each do |befores, afters, where|
      - table.with_row do |row|
        - row.with_column do
          %div{ class: "flex flex-col gap-1" }
            - befores.each do |token|
              %code= token
        - row.with_column do
          %div{ class: "flex flex-col gap-1" }
            - afters.each do |token|
              %code= token
        - row.with_column do
          = where

.mt-4.prose
  :markdown
    One thing does **not** change: the rendered HTML. The emitted CSS
    classes (`navbar-start`, `timeline-end`, ...) are DaisyUI's own
    selectors, so your stylesheets keep working untouched — the rename is
    confined to the Ruby API.

- # Before / after, side by side on wide screens.
.mt-6.max-w-4xl
  %div{ class: "grid gap-4 lg:grid-cols-2" }
    %div
      = daisy_badge("Before", css: "badge-ghost mb-2")
      = doc_code(language: "haml") do
        :plain
          = daisy_text_input(name: "username", start: "Username:")
          = daisy_checkbox(name: "terms", end: "I agree")
          = daisy_navbar do |navbar|
            - navbar.with_start do
              Logo
          = daisy_timeline do |timeline|
            - timeline.with_event(start: "1984", end: "Born")
    %div
      = daisy_badge("After", css: "badge-primary mb-2")
      = doc_code(language: "haml") do
        :plain
          = daisy_text_input(name: "username", leading: "Username:")
          = daisy_checkbox(name: "terms", trailing: "I agree")
          = daisy_navbar do |navbar|
            - navbar.with_leading do
              Logo
          = daisy_timeline do |timeline|
            - timeline.with_event(leading: "1984", trailing: "Born")

.mt-8.prose
  %h3{ class: "flex flex-col items-start gap-2" }
    = daisy_badge("Automated", css: "badge-success badge-soft")
    %span Let the migration task do it
  :markdown
    v0.7.0 ships a rake task that performs the rename for you. It scans
    `app/` and rewrites only usage it can confidently attribute to the
    renamed components above. Run it without arguments for a dry-run
    report, then apply:

.max-w-prose
  = daisy_code(css: "my-4") do |code|
    - code.with_line(prefix: "$") do
      bin/rails loco_motion:migrate:leading_trailing
    - code.with_line(prefix: "#", css: "opacity-60") do
      review the dry-run report, then...
    - code.with_line(prefix: "$") do
      APPLY=1 bin/rails loco_motion:migrate:leading_trailing

.max-w-prose.mt-4
  = daisy_alert(icon: "exclamation-triangle", css: "alert-warning") do
    %div
      %strong Review the diff before committing.
      Anything the task cannot safely attribute is printed under "Needs
      manual review" instead of rewritten.

.max-w-prose.mt-4
  = daisy_alert(icon: "information-circle", css: "alert-info") do
    %div
      %strong Your own components' start / end slots are yours
      — the task only rewrites calls it can trace to a LocoMotion
      component and reports everything else for manual review.

.mt-8.prose
  :markdown
    ### Manual follow-ups

    - **Prose and headings**: comments, docs, or UI copy that *talk about*
      the `start` / `end` labels (the task only rewrites code).
    - **Custom components** that include
      `LocoMotion::Concerns::LabelableComponent`: the parts, slots, and
      predicates are renamed too — `has_start_label?` / `has_end_label?`
      are now `has_leading_label?` / `has_trailing_label?`.
    - **Direct component renders** (`TimelineEventComponent.new(start: ...)`)
      and **system / e2e tests** that assert on the old markup or wording.

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "icons", class: "flex flex-col items-start gap-2 scroll-mt-24" }
    = daisy_badge("Breaking", css: "badge-error badge-soft")
    %span
      3. Icons:
      %code hero_icon
      is gone, meet
      %code loco_icon
  :markdown
    LocoMotion no longer bundles `rails_heroicon`. Every icon — including
    the ones components render via `icon:` options — now resolves through
    the pluggable `loco_icon` engine, which reads SVGs synced into your own
    app. The short version:

    1. **Sync your icons once** and commit the SVGs:
       `bin/rails loco_motion:icons:add heroicons` (or
       `loco_motion:icons:sync` to vendor only the icons you use).
    2. **Rename `hero_icon` / `heroicon` calls to `loco_icon`.**
    3. **Replace `Hero::IconComponent`** with `loco_icon("name")` — the
       component and the `Hero` module are removed.
    4. **Fold `variant:` / `library:` into the icon token** —
       `loco_icon("bolt", variant: :solid)` becomes
       `loco_icon("bolt/solid")`, and `icon_options: { variant: :solid }`
       becomes `icon: "name/solid"`. Passing `variant:` or `library:` now
       raises an `ArgumentError`. The Dock section's `icon_variant:` option
       is likewise replaced by the token form (`icon: "home/solid"`).

    Component `icon:` options work with **zero setup for the bundled set**
    (the chrome icons plus the standard Alert icons); anything else needs
    the one-time sync from step 1.

= daisy_button "Read the full icon migration guide", css: "btn-secondary btn-soft btn-sm mt-4", right_icon: "arrow-right", href: doc_path("migrating_icons"), turbo_frame: "_top", turbo_action: "advance", action: "click->nav#refresh"

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "checkboxes", class: "flex flex-col items-start gap-2 scroll-mt-24" }
    = daisy_badge("Behavior change", css: "badge-warning badge-soft")
    %span 4. Checkboxes and toggles now submit an unchecked value
  :markdown
    A named, enabled `daisy_checkbox` / `daisy_toggle` now renders a
    companion `<input type="hidden" value="0">` before the checkbox — the
    same trick as Rails' own `check_box` — so an *unchecked* box still
    submits a value and "uncheck to disable" forms work without hand-rolled
    `hidden_field_tag` pairs.

    If you already added your own hidden field (or your controller expects
    the parameter to be absent), opt out with `include_hidden: false`, or
    change the submitted value with `unchecked_value:`. Request specs and
    system tests that assert the exact rendered markup or posted params may
    need updating.

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "whats-new", class: "flex flex-col items-start gap-2 scroll-mt-24" }
    = daisy_badge("No action needed", css: "badge-success badge-soft")
    %span 5. New in 0.7.0
  :markdown
    Everything below ships in 0.7.0 and works without any changes to your
    app — click through to each component's examples.

.mt-6{ class: "grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3" }
